<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="191" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1210,1739]" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,275,1210,1235]" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Morphologically, 
<emphasis box="[499,616,1211,1234]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">
<taxonomicName authority="Singh &amp; Joshi &amp; Ahmad, 2018" authorityName="Singh &amp; Joshi &amp; Ahmad" authorityYear="2018" box="[499,612,1211,1234]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Neoaloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cernyi" status="sp. nov.">N. cernyi</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[631,728,1210,1235]" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[631,728,1210,1235]" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is closely similar to its congeners, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hampson" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[1177,1340,1211,1235]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Neoaloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavimargo">
<emphasis box="[1177,1340,1211,1235]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">N. flavimargo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Singh, Kirti &amp; Kaleka" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Neoaloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudoflavimargo">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">N. pseudoflavimargo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished by the following characters: in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Singh &amp; Joshi &amp; Ahmad" authorityYear="2018" box="[1032,1139,1247,1270]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Neoaloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cernyi">
<emphasis box="[1032,1139,1247,1270]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">N. cernyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1158,1218,1246,1271]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1893,1914]" captionTargetBox="[172,1425,221,1827]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[152,1435,194,1850]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Adults: 1, Neoaloa cernyi Singh &amp; Joshi, sp. nov. holotype, ♂, VTR, Bihar, India; 2, Neoaloa flavimargo (Hampson), ♂, Mae Hong Son, NW Thailand (photo by Dr Karel Ĉerný); 3, Neoaloa pseudoflavimargo Singh, Kirti &amp; Kaleka, holotype, ♂, Jatinga, NE India; 4, Paramsacta moorei (Butler), ♂, Rohtas, Bihar, India; 5, Aloa lactinea (Cramer) ♂, Waghai, Gujarat; Aloa collaris Hampson, ♂, Sarkaghat, Himachal Pradesh, India" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1436753/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">Fig.1</figureCitation>
) marginal band of hindwing is narrow and extends from apex to tornus. Whereas, in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hampson" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[923,1081,1283,1307]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Neoaloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavimargo">
<emphasis box="[923,1081,1283,1307]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">N. flavimargo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1099,1170,1282,1307]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1893,1914]" captionTargetBox="[172,1425,221,1827]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[152,1435,194,1850]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Adults: 1, Neoaloa cernyi Singh &amp; Joshi, sp. nov. holotype, ♂, VTR, Bihar, India; 2, Neoaloa flavimargo (Hampson), ♂, Mae Hong Son, NW Thailand (photo by Dr Karel Ĉerný); 3, Neoaloa pseudoflavimargo Singh, Kirti &amp; Kaleka, holotype, ♂, Jatinga, NE India; 4, Paramsacta moorei (Butler), ♂, Rohtas, Bihar, India; 5, Aloa lactinea (Cramer) ♂, Waghai, Gujarat; Aloa collaris Hampson, ♂, Sarkaghat, Himachal Pradesh, India" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1436753/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), the marginal band of hindwing is broader; in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Singh, Kirti &amp; Kaleka" authorityYear="2015" box="[422,655,1318,1342]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Neoaloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudoflavimargo">
<emphasis box="[422,655,1318,1342]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">N. pseudoflavimargo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[670,737,1318,1343]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1893,1914]" captionTargetBox="[172,1425,221,1827]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[152,1435,194,1850]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Adults: 1, Neoaloa cernyi Singh &amp; Joshi, sp. nov. holotype, ♂, VTR, Bihar, India; 2, Neoaloa flavimargo (Hampson), ♂, Mae Hong Son, NW Thailand (photo by Dr Karel Ĉerný); 3, Neoaloa pseudoflavimargo Singh, Kirti &amp; Kaleka, holotype, ♂, Jatinga, NE India; 4, Paramsacta moorei (Butler), ♂, Rohtas, Bihar, India; 5, Aloa lactinea (Cramer) ♂, Waghai, Gujarat; Aloa collaris Hampson, ♂, Sarkaghat, Himachal Pradesh, India" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1436753/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), the marginal band is reduced to a fine line, not reaching apex or the anal angle. In hindwing of 
<emphasis box="[537,648,1355,1378]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Singh &amp; Joshi &amp; Ahmad" authorityYear="2018" box="[537,644,1355,1378]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Neoaloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cernyi">N. cernyi</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
sub-marginal series of black spots are absent which is present in the other species of 
<emphasis box="[350,445,1390,1414]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">Neoaloa</emphasis>
. The male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authority="Singh &amp; Joshi &amp; Ahmad, 2018" authorityName="Singh &amp; Joshi &amp; Ahmad" authorityYear="2018" box="[733,842,1391,1414]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Neoaloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cernyi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[733,842,1391,1414]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">N. cernyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[854,947,1391,1414]" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<figureCitation box="[967,1039,1390,1415]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–11" captionStartId="3.[151,258,1938,1959]" captionTargetBox="[234,1391,204,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[181,1402,191,1889]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 8–11. Male genitalia: 8, Neoaloa cernyi Singh &amp; Joshi, sp. nov. holotype, ♂, VTR, Bihar, India; 9, Neoaloa flavimargo (Hampson), ♂, Mae Hong Son, NW Thailand (photo by Dr Karel Ĉerný); 10, Neoaloa pseudoflavimargo Singh, Kirti &amp; Kaleka, holotype, ♂, Jatinga, NE India; 11, Paramsacta moorei (Butler), ♂, Rohtas, Bihar, India" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1436757/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) differs clearly from those of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hampson" baseAuthorityYear="1894" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Neoaloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavimargo">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">N. flavimargo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[292,363,1426,1451]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–11" captionStartId="3.[151,258,1938,1959]" captionTargetBox="[234,1391,204,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[181,1402,191,1889]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 8–11. Male genitalia: 8, Neoaloa cernyi Singh &amp; Joshi, sp. nov. holotype, ♂, VTR, Bihar, India; 9, Neoaloa flavimargo (Hampson), ♂, Mae Hong Son, NW Thailand (photo by Dr Karel Ĉerný); 10, Neoaloa pseudoflavimargo Singh, Kirti &amp; Kaleka, holotype, ♂, Jatinga, NE India; 11, Paramsacta moorei (Butler), ♂, Rohtas, Bihar, India" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1436757/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) by reduction of mid-saccular process of right valva, presence of a small thumb like distal saccular process of right valva, the distal saccular process of left valva not bifurcate and distal costal process is shorter whereas, in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hampson" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[379,501,1499,1523]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Neoaloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavimargo">
<emphasis box="[379,501,1499,1523]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">flavimargo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
mid-saccular process of right valva is well-developed, distal saccular process of right valva is very short, distal saccular process of left valva is bifurcate and distal costal process is longer. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Singh &amp; Joshi &amp; Ahmad" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Neoaloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cernyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">Neoaloa cernyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also differs in the male genitalia from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Singh, Kirti &amp; Kaleka" authorityYear="2015" box="[691,929,1571,1595]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Neoaloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudoflavimargo">
<emphasis box="[691,929,1571,1595]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">N. pseudoflavimargo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[949,1035,1570,1595]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–11" captionStartId="3.[151,258,1938,1959]" captionTargetBox="[234,1391,204,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[181,1402,191,1889]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 8–11. Male genitalia: 8, Neoaloa cernyi Singh &amp; Joshi, sp. nov. holotype, ♂, VTR, Bihar, India; 9, Neoaloa flavimargo (Hampson), ♂, Mae Hong Son, NW Thailand (photo by Dr Karel Ĉerný); 10, Neoaloa pseudoflavimargo Singh, Kirti &amp; Kaleka, holotype, ♂, Jatinga, NE India; 11, Paramsacta moorei (Butler), ♂, Rohtas, Bihar, India" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1436757/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
) by the reduction of mid-saccular process of right valva, symmetrical mid-costal processes, presence of a small thumb like distal saccular process of right valva and broad U-shaped vinculum whereas in 
<emphasis box="[761,1003,1643,1667]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Singh, Kirti &amp; Kaleka" authorityYear="2015" box="[761,999,1643,1667]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Neoaloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudoflavimargo">N. pseudoflavimargo</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
mid-saccular process of right valva is present, mid-costal processes are asymmetrical, distal saccular process of right valva is trigonal and vinculum is slightly squarish and tilted.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1436757/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" startId="3.[151,258,1938,1959]" targetBox="[234,1391,204,1857]" targetPageId="3">
