<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="193" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1324,2033]" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,494,1324,1349]" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">Description. Adult male.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[511,590,1324,1349]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1893,1914]" captionTargetBox="[172,1425,221,1827]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[152,1435,194,1850]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Adults: 1, Neoaloa cernyi Singh &amp; Joshi, sp. nov. holotype, ♂, VTR, Bihar, India; 2, Neoaloa flavimargo (Hampson), ♂, Mae Hong Son, NW Thailand (photo by Dr Karel Ĉerný); 3, Neoaloa pseudoflavimargo Singh, Kirti &amp; Kaleka, holotype, ♂, Jatinga, NE India; 4, Paramsacta moorei (Butler), ♂, Rohtas, Bihar, India; 5, Aloa lactinea (Cramer) ♂, Waghai, Gujarat; Aloa collaris Hampson, ♂, Sarkaghat, Himachal Pradesh, India" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1436753/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[605,620,1325,1349]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="2.[151,244,956,977]" captionTargetBox="[259,1312,199,920]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[249,1321,191,926]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 7. Adults: Neoaloa cernyi sp. nov., holotype, ♂, VTR, Bihar, India (photograph of live specimen)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1436755/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">7</figureCitation>
) Forewing length 
<quantity box="[832,915,1325,1349]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="4" pageNumber="193" unit="mm" value="22.0">22 mm</quantity>
. Head with frons white, vertex scarlet. Labial palpi short, scarlet with tip black. Antennae weakly ciliated. Thorax white with a scarlet band at collar, patagia covered with scarlet and white scales; a black spot on each tegula. Forewing white with a scarlet band at costa from base to before apex, broader in middle; a black spot on upper angle of cell; termen oblique; underside same with retinaculum black. Hindwing white with a discal spot; a narrow, marginal yellow band from apex to anal angle, fringes white. Legs with costa and femur covered with scarlet and white scales, rest of the legs black, banded with white. Abdomen scarlet with dorsal black spots on each segment. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[890,1060,1540,1565]" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1075,1155,1540,1565]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–11" captionStartId="3.[151,258,1938,1959]" captionTargetBox="[234,1391,204,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[181,1402,191,1889]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 8–11. Male genitalia: 8, Neoaloa cernyi Singh &amp; Joshi, sp. nov. holotype, ♂, VTR, Bihar, India; 9, Neoaloa flavimargo (Hampson), ♂, Mae Hong Son, NW Thailand (photo by Dr Karel Ĉerný); 10, Neoaloa pseudoflavimargo Singh, Kirti &amp; Kaleka, holotype, ♂, Jatinga, NE India; 11, Paramsacta moorei (Butler), ♂, Rohtas, Bihar, India" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1436757/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">Figs. 8</figureCitation>
): uncus triangular, hoodlike, broader at base and narrowing towards apex, tip pointed; tegumen as long as vinculum; vinculum broad Ushaped; juxta with a semi-circular groove at tip. Valva slightly asymmetrical, undivided, medial area broad, flaplike, concaved from inner wall; saccular projection small; mid-costal projection strongly curved at centre, symmetrical with a line of fine spines towards distal half. Aedeagus strongly curved with apex broad; vesica with two unequal lobes, large basal lobe with a large patch of compactly placed spines and a small patch of spines towards aedeagus, smaller apical lobe with tightly packed large patch of spines and a small patch of spines; fields of scobination also present.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="193" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1324,2033]" box="[199,1351,1828,1853]" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1828,1853]" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">Etymology:</emphasis>
The species is named after eminent Arctiid worker Dr. Karel Černý of Innsbruck, 
<collectingCountry box="[1261,1347,1828,1853]" name="Austria" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">Austria</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1324,2033]" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,408,1864,1889]" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">Taxonomic notes:</emphasis>
Originally, 
<taxonomicName authority="Hampson, 1891" authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1891" box="[541,809,1864,1889]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Aloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="193" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="collaris">
<emphasis box="[541,626,1864,1888]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">collaris</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[633,809,1865,1889]" pageId="4" pageNumber="193" refId="ref1503" refString="Hampson, G. F. (1891) The Lepidoptera Heterocera of the Nilgiri districts. In: Illustrations of typical specimens of Lepidoptera Heterocera in the collections of British Museum. Uol. 8. Tylor and Francis Ltd., London, pp. 1 - 144," type="book chapter">Hampson, 1891</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[824,902,1864,1889]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1893,1914]" captionTargetBox="[172,1425,221,1827]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[152,1435,194,1850]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Adults: 1, Neoaloa cernyi Singh &amp; Joshi, sp. nov. holotype, ♂, VTR, Bihar, India; 2, Neoaloa flavimargo (Hampson), ♂, Mae Hong Son, NW Thailand (photo by Dr Karel Ĉerný); 3, Neoaloa pseudoflavimargo Singh, Kirti &amp; Kaleka, holotype, ♂, Jatinga, NE India; 4, Paramsacta moorei (Butler), ♂, Rohtas, Bihar, India; 5, Aloa lactinea (Cramer) ♂, Waghai, Gujarat; Aloa collaris Hampson, ♂, Sarkaghat, Himachal Pradesh, India" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1436753/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">Figs. 6</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[914,943,1865,1889]" captionStart="FIGURES 12–13" captionStartId="4.[151,258,1184,1205]" captionTargetBox="[165,1418,217,1135]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[152,1435,194,1170]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 12–13. Male genitalia: 12, Aloa lactinea (Cramer) ♂, Waghai, Gujarat; 13, Aloa collaris Hampson, ♂, Sarkaghat, Himachal Pradesh, India." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1436759/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">13</figureCitation>
) was described under genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1855" box="[1262,1315,1864,1888]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Aloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="193" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1262,1315,1864,1888]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">Aloa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation pageId="4" pageNumber="193" refId="ref1554" refString="Hampson, G. F. (1894) The Fauna of British India, including Ceylon and Burma. Moths. Uol. 2. Taylor and Francis, London, 609 pp." type="book">Hampson (1894</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation box="[233,290,1901,1925]" pageId="4" pageNumber="193" refId="ref1589" refString="Hampson, G. F. (1900) Catalogue of the Lepidoptera Phalaenae in the British Museum. Uol. 2. British Museum of Natural History, London, 589 pp" type="book">1900</bibRefCitation>
) treated it under 
<taxonomicName authority="Hubner, [1819]" authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1819" box="[491,812,1900,1925]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Creatonotos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="193" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[491,629,1901,1924]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">Creatonotos</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[638,812,1900,1925]" pageId="4" pageNumber="193" refId="ref1667" refString="Hubner, J. ([1819] 1816) Uerzeichnis bekiannter Schmetterlinge. bey dem Verfasser zu Finden, Augsburg, 431 pp." type="book">Hübner, [1819]</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
1816 and 
<taxonomicName authority="Walker, 1855" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1855" box="[937,1197,1900,1925]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Amsacta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="193" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[937,1033,1901,1924]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">Amsacta</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[1043,1197,1900,1925]" pageId="4" pageNumber="193" refId="ref1773" refString="Walker, F. (1855) Lepidoptera Heterocera. List of the specimens of Lepidopterous Insects in the collection of the British Museum London, 3, 583 - 131." type="book">Walker, 1855</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, respectively. Lastly, 
<bibRefCitation box="[151,350,1936,1961]" pageId="4" pageNumber="193" refId="ref1453" refString="Dubatolov, V. V. (2004) A new genus is established for Bombyx lineola Fabricius, 1793, with systematic notes on the genus Aloa Walker, 1855 (Lepidoptera: Arctiidae). Atlanta, 35 (3 / 4), 403 - 413." type="journal article">Dubatolov (2004)</bibRefCitation>
shifted 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1891" box="[439,524,1936,1960]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Aloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="193" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="collaris">
<emphasis box="[439,524,1936,1960]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">collaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
under 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hulstaert" authorityYear="1923" box="[602,737,1937,1960]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Paramsacta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="193" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[602,737,1937,1960]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">Paramsacta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with doubtful condition. During the present work, the external male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1891" box="[345,430,1973,1997]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Aloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="193" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="collaris">
<emphasis box="[345,430,1973,1997]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">collaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are studied and as a result, its original combination, 
<taxonomicName authority="Hampson, 1891" authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1891" box="[1020,1352,1973,1997]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Aloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="193" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="collaris">
<emphasis box="[1020,1165,1973,1997]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">Aloa collaris</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[1172,1352,1973,1997]" pageId="4" pageNumber="193" refId="ref1503" refString="Hampson, G. F. (1891) The Lepidoptera Heterocera of the Nilgiri districts. In: Illustrations of typical specimens of Lepidoptera Heterocera in the collections of British Museum. Uol. 8. Tylor and Francis Ltd., London, pp. 1 - 144," type="book chapter">Hampson, 1891</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="193">comb. rev.</emphasis>
is restored.
</paragraph>
